  "prompt": "What is the difference between DNC and CNC?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between DNC (Distributed Numerical Control) and CNC (Computer Numerical Control):\n\nDNC (Distributed Numerical Control):\n1. Manages multiple CNC machines from a central computer\n2. Transfers and stores programs for multiple machines\n3. Coordinates machining operations across different machines\n4. Used in larger manufacturing environments\n5. Facilitates centralized program management and distribution\n6. Allows real-time monitoring of multiple machines\n7. More complex networking infrastructure\n\nCNC (Computer Numerical Control):\n1. Controls individual machine tool operations\n2. Operates a single machine using programmed instructions\n3. Converts digital design into precise mechanical movements\n4. Used for specific machining tasks on individual machines\n5. Provides direct control over cutting, milling, turning processes\n6. Allows high precision and repeatability\n7. More focused on individual machine performance\n\nPrimary Difference:\n- DNC manages multiple machines centrally\n- CNC controls individual machine operations\n\nBoth technologies are essential in modern manufacturing, with DNC providing broader coordination and CNC offering precise machine control.",
